enitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","History: Joseph Jenks (1602–83), the descendant of an old Welsh family, was born in England and traveled to Saugus, near Lynn, MA, in 1642 to assist in the development of America's first iron works. His son, Joseph Jenckes (sic), followed in 1650, founded Pawtucket, RI, and raised four sons who held places of respect and distinction in RI, including one who served as governor for five years."]},{"name":"Jenkinson","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): from the Middle English personal names <i>Jankin</i>, <i>Jenkin</i>, or <i>Jonkin</i> (see   Jenkin  ) + <i>son</i>."]}]},{"name":"Gwladys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old form of   Gladys  , of uncertain derivation."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Gronwy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name of uncertain derivation, borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by  Goronwy the Staunch , Lord of Penllyn. He became the lover of the flower-maiden Blodeuedd and murdered her husband  Lleu Llaw Gyffes , but Lleu was later restored to life and definitively dispatched Goronwy."],"variants":[{"name":"Gronw","meanings":["Variant of   Goronwy ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gwladys Gronwy verch Jenkin was born about 1127, in Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Lonas ap Gronwy Lord of Llanerch. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1127–":"umbes 1127–Surnud","1122–Male":"1122–Surnud","1295–1373":"1295–1373","1127–Female":"1127–Surnud","1127":"1127","about 1127":"umbes 1127","1122":"1122","1373":"1373","1295":"1295","Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llandovery, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Penley, Wales":"Penley, Flintshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1127–":"noin 1127–Kuollut","1122–Male":"1122–Kuollut","1295–1373":"1295–